I played around all fall with a few salmon patterns and found some that I liked. For the most part, anything that was forward heavy would strip and dive ok and lead to some good eats. I found a lot of luck with an adaptation of the Comet pattern. I found more luck the further departed I got. Here's one I'm starting to call the Poodle Comet. It's a smart, loyal, albeit weird looking fly. And it's on a tube, which is my pet favorite to tie. In keeping with what I learned this fall, coho (and most salmon c'mon) love action. Coho especially. The more it jigs and jives, the better. For a tube fly to do that, raw tungsten as far forward as possible and sparse materials everywhere else are necessary. I wouldn't be surprised if someone has already done this pattern a thousand times over but for now, I'm calling it the Poodle Comet. Hint: this thing also hunts tied on a raw hook, just swap out the disc for dumbbell eyes. Dives even faster.

I work at a desk behind a computer. I enjoy my work most of the time even though most of the time it does in fact feel like work. Until recently, I sometimes considered that all the hours spent desk jockeying would eventually result in something like carpal tunnel as the hours turn to days, then months, then years of repetitive micro movements straining the nerves and other tissues I depend on when I'm not working. In other words, the stuff that I don't live for would impact the stuff I do live for. Specifically, fly fishing.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
A recent trip put any fear that moving a mouse would be the cause of an ailment that might interrupt my fly fishing obsession to rest! After fighting dozens of coho a day on a 6 weight (the 8 weight broke), in the rain and cold for 10 days straight, no feeling has returned to the fingers on my right hand. It's since been a couple months of PT, and a recent nerve test confirmed moderate carpal tunnel... Carpal tunnel from fly fishing! I don't know if I'm more thankful that this happened from fishing and not from work or that I can still tie and cast despite the zappy sensation of a damaged nerve. Thankful for all those things I guess.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Happy Friday friends and remember to stretch before casting 😂. Now back to nerve exercises.

There are a thousand caddis patterns out there but this Caddisfaction might be my favorite. For one, it's pretty realistic. For another, it's original. But mostly, as a tyer, it really scratches that complicated-but-easy-enough-to-be-a-guidefly itch. Something that imitates natural insect well and is quick to tie. I'll post another tying video in the coming days but here's the short version if you'd like to give it a try (a low budget video is a few posts back):
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Recipe:
- Partridge Standard Dry Fly hook, sz12 (I like a shorter shank but longer works too, you just need a longer dubbing loop)
- CDC feather wound around the hook for a body (don't trim the long feathers, stroke them back and let them trail. This creates visible CDC mixed throughout the body)
- Snowshoe rabbit in light dun and contrasting deer hair in a dubbing loop. Make the loop before tying in the CDC feather. Then add the rabbit and deer into the loop and wind forward. It's easier to stack multiple materials on top of each other in a loop if you have two good material clips, like the Swiss CDC ones. Pricey but worth it. 
- Hemingway's deer hair dubbing thorax, also in a loop
- Good quality pheasant tail antennae, like Nature's Spirit natural or brown
- strong thread so you can make the loops without bulk. I like Semperfli 30D nano-silk. You can split the thread and add the materials into the split eliminating the need for a loop and the associated bulk for smaller size flies like sz16
- trim the hair on the underside
-done. Go fish

While I possess a range of threads 95% of thread I tie with comes off a bulk white spool like this one. The trick? Colored markers. So easy. There are two downsides to this method. First, it takes a little extra time to pop off the cap of a marker and color the thread when you need to. This is usually needed for collars, after building a thread dam, and for finishing. The tips of my bobbins also tend to pick up some color so they definitely don't look like new anymore! Second, is that marker-colored thread doesn't hold onto color as well as true dyed threads. This can be mitigated to some degree by using UV resin or head cement to "lock in" the marker color.

Two tips if you're gonna give this body style a try:
1. Use a dab of super glue to get the mylar to lay down along the top of the hook. This will keep it from shifting when you apply the resin
2. Wind the quill very quickly (on a rotary vise if you can). If you use enough resin to create the bulges it will spread out over the quill pretty quickly. Wrap fast and hit it with a UV light quickly.
